content.text: MySQL ANY and ALL Operators
The MySQL ANY and ALL Operators
The ANY and ALL operators allow you to perform a comparison between a single column value and a range of other values.
content.html: The ANY and ALL operators allow you to perform a comparison between a single column value and a range of other values.

content.text: The ANY Operator
The ANY operator:
ANY means that the condition will be true if the operation is true for any of the values in the range.
content.html: ANY means that the condition will be true if the operation is true for any of the values in the range.

content.text: ANY Syntax

syntaxHighlighting.text:
SELECT column_name(s)
  FROM table_name
  WHERE 
  column_name operator ANY  (SELECT column_name  FROM table_name  WHERE
  condition);

content.text: Note: The operator must be a standard comparison operator (=, <>, !=, >, >=, <, or <=).
content.html: Note: The operator must be a standard comparison operator (=, <>, !=, >, >=, <, or <=).

content.text: The ALL Operator
The ALL operator:
ALL means that the condition will be true only if the operation is true for all values in the range.
content.html: ALL means that the condition will be true only if the operation is true for all values in the range.

content.text: ALL Syntax With SELECT
